3. Which animal groups are represented in the data? Make a plot that shows the number in each class.

ggplot(data = homerange, mapping = aes(x = taxon)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = taxon)) + labs(title = "Animal Groups Represented in Homerange Data")

4. Are there more carnivores or herbivores represented in the data? Make a plot that shows the number in each trophic guild.

homerange %>% filter(trophic.guild == "carnivore" | trophic.guild == "herbivore") %>% ggplot(data = homerange, mapping = aes(x = trophic.guild)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = trophic.guild)) + labs(title = "Amount of Carnivores compared to Herbivores in Homerange Data")

5. Which herbivorous mammals have homeranges greater than 1,000,000 m? Show only the common name, order, mean homerange size, and mean body mass. Arrange the data in descending order by homerange size and show only the top 10 species.

homerange %>% filter(mean.hra.m2 > 1000000) %>% select(common.name, order, mean.hra.m2, mean.mass.g) %>% arrange(desc(mean.hra.m2)) %>% slice_max(mean.hra.m2, n=10)

6. Which two species have the largest and smallest homerange sizes?

homerange %>% filter(mean.hra.m2 > 1000000) %>% select(common.name, order, mean.hra.m2, mean.mass.g) %>% arrange(desc(mean.hra.m2)) %>% slice_max(mean.hra.m2, n=1)
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   common.name order        mean.hra.m2 mean.mass.g
##   <chr>       <chr>              <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 reindeer    artiodactyla  3550830977     102059.
homerange %>% filter(mean.hra.m2 > 1000000) %>% select(common.name, order, mean.hra.m2, mean.mass.g) %>% arrange(desc(mean.hra.m2)) %>% slice_min(mean.hra.m2, n=1)

8. Is there a relationship between body mass and homerange size? Make a scatterplot to show this relationship. Be sure to include appropriate labels and a title.

names(homerange)
##  [1] "taxon"                      "common.name"               
##  [3] "class"                      "order"                     
##  [5] "family"                     "genus"                     
##  [7] "species"                    "primarymethod"             
##  [9] "N"                          "mean.mass.g"               
## [11] "log10.mass"                 "alternative.mass.reference"
## [13] "mean.hra.m2"                "log10.hra"                 
## [15] "hra.reference"              "realm"                     
## [17] "thermoregulation"           "locomotion"                
## [19] "trophic.guild"              "dimension"                 
## [21] "preymass"                   "log10.preymass"            
## [23] "PPMR"                       "prey.size.reference"
homerange %>% select(mean.mass.g, mean.hra.m2) %>% ggplot(data = homerange, mapping = aes(x = mean.mass.g, y = mean.hra.m2)) + geom_point() +labs(title = "Relationship Between Body Mass and Homerange Size", x = "Mean Mass (g)", y = "Mean Homerange Size (m^2)") + scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10()

9. Use filter to extract the data for only birds and mammals. Then make a plot that compares the homerange sizes of these two groups. Be sure to include appropriate labels and a title.

filter(homerange, taxon == "birds" | taxon == "mammals") %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x = taxon, y = mean.hra.m2)) + geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(fill = taxon)) + labs(title = "Homerange Sizes of Birds and Mammals", x = "Taxon", y = "Homerange Size") + scale_y_log10()

"Are there more carnivorous ectotherms or endotherms?"
